{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01EsaBrjTZRSKT2JDZFg3WYp","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I understand the current state:\n1. The 3 existing nodes have `node.attr.tier: hot`\n2. The `app-data` index has `allocation.require.tier: hot` - so shards will only be on nodes with `tier: hot`\n3. I need to add 2 new data nodes with a different allocation attribute (e.g., `tier: warm`)\n4. I need to configure shard routing to move shards to the new nodes\n\nThe plan:\n1. Create a new ConfigMap for the new nodes (e.g., `es-config-warm`) with `node.attr.tier: warm`\n2. Create a new StatefulSet `es-data-warm` with 2 replicas using the new config\n3. Update the `app-data` index routing to allow new nodes (change `require.tier: hot` to include `warm` or remove the requirement)\n4. Wait for shards to relocate\n\nFor the new nodes, I need to ensure they're configured as data nodes with the `tier: warm` attribute, connect to the same cluster, and use the same discovery seed hosts so they join properly.\n\nThe tricky part is discovery—the existing master nodes only know about `es-cluster-0`, `es-cluster-1`, and `es-cluster-2`. When the new `es-data-warm` pods start, they need to find the cluster. I can either add the new pod DNS names to the seed hosts, or rely on the new nodes discovering the existing masters through the initial seed hosts and then joining the cluster.\n\nFor the index routing, I need to update the `app-data` index settings to allow shards on the warm tier nodes. I can either remove the `tier: hot` requirement entirely or change it to `tier: warm` so the shards migrate to the new nodes.\n\nHowever, if I set it to `tier: warm` only with just 2 new nodes, I run into a constraint issue—with 3 primary shards and 1 replica each (6 total shards), Elasticsearch won't place a primary and its replica on the same node, so 2 nodes might not have enough capacity to hold all the shards.\n\nActually, thinking through the math: 2 nodes can handle this by distributing 2 primaries on one node with 1 replica, and 1 primary on the other with 2 replicas. That works fine.\n\nThe real question is whether removing the `require.tier: hot` constraint entirely and letting shards rebalance naturally is better than forcing them to warm tier, since the verification only confirms some app-data shards moved to the new nodes, not necessarily all of them.\n\nI'll go with adding new warm nodes and updating the index routing to use `require.tier: warm` instead, which will push all shards to the new nodes and work with the replica count across 2 nodes.\n\nNow I need to set up the services and configuration for the new StatefulSet. I'll create a headless service called `es-data-warm` so the pods can discover each other via DNS, and the new nodes will reference the existing master nodes for cluster discovery. I'm creating a ConfigMap that sets the cluster name, assigns the warm tier attribute, and configures the node roles as data and ingest. Writing Kubernetes manifests... Configuring resource requests and limits for the container, then setting up a persistent volume claim for the data storage. Next, I need to update the index routing settings to include the warm tier nodes instead of just requiring the hot tier.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":779,"cache_read_input_tokens":31750,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":779},"output_tokens":12,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"bba571d1-b0f7-4073-af95-60798e41d957","uuid":"a10343af-0b67-490d-9333-4e1d917feee6","request_id":"req_011CcMUniR4iXtcn3Ak45qKU"}
